      <p style="text-align: justify;">According to the general criteria of this edition, the transcriptions retain the original note values. As
                with most of secular music of the time, Marenzio&#x2019;s madrigals of the Book IV <hi rend="italic">a 6</hi> are in <hi style="font-family:Musica Wolfgang">u</hi>,
                implying a semibreve tactus. Thus, the pieces are barred at the semibreve, each modern measure containing one tactus.<note place="foot" xml:id="ftn1" n="1"><p rend="footnote text"> For a survey of the use of mensuration signs in Marenzio&#x2019;s madrigals and its meaning see
                        Ruth DeFord, &#x201C;<hi style="font-family:Musica Wolfgang" xml:space="preserve">u </hi>and&#xA0;
                        <hi style="font-family:Musica Wolfgang" xml:space="preserve">p </hi>in the Madrigals of Marenzio,&#x201D; in<hi rend="italic">&#x201C;Compositor
                            moderno e vago&#x201D;: Perspectives on Luca Marenzio&#x2019;s Secular and Devotional Music</hi>, ed. Mauro Calcagno (Turnaut: Brepols, 2014),
                        43&#x2013;64.</p></note> The only exception is n. 6, <hi rend="italic">Crudel, perch&#xE9; mi fuggi</hi>, which bears the mensuration sign <hi style="font-family:Musica Wolfgang">p</hi>. The reason for this is not entirely clear: the <hi style="font-family:Musica Wolfgang">p</hi> could be due to the seriousness of the text, or to the pattern of breves and dotted semibreves followed by minims in the second
                part of the piece. Still, the number of syllabic minims and semiminims does strongly suggest a semibreve tactus; thus the piece has been
                barred at the semibreve as well.&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;</p>
